It would be related to this:

```vala
// vala/valamethodtype.vala

public override Symbol? get_member (string member_name) {
	if (method_symbol.coroutine && member_name == "begin") {
		return method_symbol;
	} else if (method_symbol.coroutine && member_name == "end") {
		return method_symbol;
	} else if (method_symbol.coroutine && member_name == "callback") {
		return method_symbol.get_callback_method ();
	}
	return null;
}
```

If I make it return `method_symbol.get_end_method()` instead of `method_symbol` for end methods, `FinishFunc f = foo.end;` in the example works. It however causes some tests to fail.

@lillolollo 
this bug report is a duplicate of 
#3091 Folders are shown as files in file dialog icons

I'm also seeing this on windows with a build of v3.22 that I made using the vcpkg system recommended by https://www.gtk.org/download/windows.php

Swapping the order of freeing the last event and unref'ing the context fixes the issue for me:

```
  if (info->last_event)
  {
      gdk_event_free (info->last_event);
      info->last_event = NULL;
  }

  gtk_drag_clear_source_info (info->context);
  g_object_unref (info->context);
```

No more crash.

- for the sake of coherence, radios and checks should probably be of the same blue  as the one used elsewhere in Gnome theme (i.e. the blue used to indicate the selected elements);
- however, the current blue from the Gnome theme may not contrast enough with dark backgrounds. This is especially important in dark themes/modes (be it general or specific to an app). I suggest a more clear or shocking blue for the whole Gnome theme;
- also, specifically concerning radios, I don’t understand the different sizes between the “sphere” in switches, the sphere from “progressing bars”, the “ball” to close apps in AppOverview, and radios. If we are to adopt a scientific/objective approach, one size could probably be understood as a bit more adequate that another. Things should then be harmonised in gnome theme according to that specific chosen size.

I just wanted to add to this request the following - I would suggest for Lollypop the following options :
- permanently hide the sidebar (@reece.dews request);
- show/hide the sidebar whenever the cursor reaches the right side (and/or with a keyboard shortcut);
- permanently show or hide labels/text next to the icons.

I suggest this last option for three reasons : (1) because users may have difficulties to understand and/or remember right away what all icons are supposed to represent ; (2) because icons + text is the standard for gnome apps (Files, Settings, etc.) and Lollypop would be consistent with them; and (3) because users may still like more or be more used to the previous Lollypop sidebar (whereas, allowing this option shouldn't harm those that prefer the new sidebar). Obviously the first 2 options (permanently hide the sidebar, and show/hide the sidebar on demand) would equally be applicable to a sidebar with labels/text.

So I feel like I should not open a new request, but only complement this one, unless necessary.

